SECOND REGULAR SESSION
[PERFECTED]
HOUSE COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE FOR
HOUSE BILL NO. 1840
103RD GENERAL ASSEMBLY
4186H.03P JOSEPH ENGLER, Chief Clerk
AN ACT
To amend chapter 650, RSMo, by adding thereto one new section relating to the
establishment of an alert system for missing persons with developmental
disabilities, with an emergency clause.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the state of Missouri, as follows:
Section A. Chapter 650, RSMo, is amended by adding thereto one new section, to be
2 known as section 650.535, to read as follows:
650.535. 1. This section shall be known and may be cited as "RJ's Law".
2 2. There is hereby created within the department of public safety a statewide
3 program called the "Purple Alert System" to aid in the identification and location of
4 missing persons with developmental disabilities whose disappearance poses a credible
5 threat of immediate danger or serious bodily harm to themselves through immediate
6 and effective community and emergency response.
7 3. For purposes of this section, "developmental disability" includes the
8 following:
9 (1) A mental or cognitive disability, which shall not include, for persons sixty
10 years of age or older, Alzheimer's disease or a dementia-related disorder;
11 (2) An intellectual disability;
12 (3) A brain injury;
13 (4) Other physical, mental, or emotional disabilities that are not related to
14 substance abuse; or
15 (5) Any combination of such conditions.
EXPLANATION — Matter enclosed in bold-faced brackets [thus] in the above bill is not enacted and is
intended to be omitted from the law. Matter in bold-face type in the above bill is proposed language.

HCS HB 1840 2
16 4. Before July 1, 2027, the department of public safety, in cooperation with the
17 Missouri state highway patrol, department of transportation, department of health and
18 senior services, the state lottery, and local law enforcement agencies shall:
19 (1) Develop a training program and alert system for missing persons who have
20 developmental disabilities that is compatible with existing alert systems in the state. The
21 training program shall implement crisis intervention team training to equip law
22 enforcement officers with the skills necessary to understand developmental disabilities,
23 to de-escalate interactions with persons in crisis, to facilitate appropriate interventions,
24 and to respond effectively to a reported missing person emergency when the person has
25 a developmental disability;
26 (2) Establish policies and procedures for responding to a reported missing
27 person emergency when the person has a developmental disability. The policies shall, at
28 a minimum, provide for the following:
29 (a) Immediate and widespread dissemination of critical information when a
30 person who has a developmental disability is reported missing;
31 (b) Enhancement of emergency response teams' competence by informing them
32 of the unique behaviors and needs of persons with developmental disabilities; and
33 (c) Measures to increase public awareness and understanding of the risks
34 associated with developmental disability-related elopement to foster community support
35 for persons with developmental disabilities; and
36 (3) Require a law enforcement agency to do the following, at a minimum, upon
37 receiving a report:
38 (a) Contact media outlets in the affected area or surrounding jurisdictions;
39 (b) Inform all on-duty law enforcement officers of the reported missing person
40 with a developmental disability; and
41 (c) Communicate the report to all other law enforcement agencies in the counties
42 surrounding the county in which the report is filed.
43 5. The department of public safety shall administer and promulgate rules for the
44 implementation of the alert system established under this section. Any rule or portion
45 of a rule, as that term is defined in section 536.010, that is created under the authority
46 delegated in this section shall become effective only if it complies with and is subject to
47 all of the provisions of chapter 536 and, if applicable, section 536.028. This section and
48 chapter 536 are nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with the general assembly
49 pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to delay the effective date, or to disapprove and annul
50 a rule are subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of rulemaking authority
51 and any rule proposed or adopted after August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.

HCS HB 1840 3
Section B. Because immediate action is necessary to protect persons with disabilities,
2 section A of this act is deemed necessary for the immediate preservation of the public health,
3 welfare, peace, and safety, and is hereby declared to be an emergency act within the meaning
4 of the constitution, and section A of this act shall be in full force and effect upon its passage
5 and approval.
